text: Madison Avenue, east side, from 39th to 40th Streets. Only No. 265, the corner house at 39th Street, will remain in 1935. In the center of the block Nos. 269-71 will shortly be replaced by two story Thibault (wall papers) showroom, then in 1927 a tall office building will be erected. Between this and the 39th Street corner house, No. 267 ("Floor for rent" sign) will be replaced about 1929 by a small structure. Another tall building will be erected 1930-31 on site of 275-77, S.E. corner of 40th Street. Buildings on N.E. corner of 40th Street were demolished in 1925. About 1920.

23, 25, 27 East 39th Street, north side, between Madison and Park Avenues. The Zeta Psi Club has just vacated No. 25 and moved into No. 31, which is not shown in this view.
October, 1921.

Gift of E. M. Jenks.
Madison Avenue, at S.E. Corner of 39th Street. The Soldiers' and Sailors' Club is at No. 261. No. 257 is the Delta Tau Delta Club. These buildings were demolished in August, 1931. 1921.

269-71 Madison Avenue, east side, between 39th and 40th Streets, a new building, awarded silver medal. Trowbridge and Livingston were the architects. This building replaces two old residences. Its facade will be used in 1927 as the base for a 22-story office building.

About 1921.

Gift of E. M. Jenks.
